{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17494338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17494338"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:41:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:41:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1330"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1330"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0,0.1,0.06,0.83]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91995"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1330"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75458"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5757"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31422"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91995"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA nurse approaches a doctor in the ward of a hospital in which they both work. The nurse is a 45-year-old man who wants the doctor to write a prescription for himself. He asks the doctor to renew his six-monthly prescription for captopril, which he takes for hypertension. He explains he has been taking this medication for several years but is too busy to visit his general practitioner for a prescription renewal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate response from the doctor?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provide samples from ward stock","Write a six-month prescription","Write a one-month prescription with advice to see his general practitioner","Check blood pressure and prescribe accordingly","Advise consultation with his general practitioner"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario highlights the ethical challenges that arise when healthcare workers are asked to provide informal medical care to colleagues. The most appropriate response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadvise consultation with his general practitioner\u003C/strong\u003E. This maintains professional boundaries and ensures proper continuity of care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWriting a six-month prescription\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it bypasses the important regular review process that should occur with chronic conditions like hypertension. It also creates a potentially problematic doctor-patient relationship with a colleague.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWriting a one-month prescription\u003C/strong\u003E might seem like a compromise but still constitutes inappropriate informal care and could enable delay in proper medical review.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChecking blood pressure and prescribing accordingly\u003C/strong\u003E would be establishing a doctor-patient relationship in an informal setting without access to medical records or proper consultation facilities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding samples from ward stock\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially illegal, as hospital supplies are intended for inpatient use only.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Medical Board of Australia\u0027s Good Medical Practice guide specifically advises against treating those with whom you have a close personal relationship. This includes colleagues, as emotional proximity can compromise clinical objectivity and professional boundaries. Additionally, chronic conditions like hypertension require regular monitoring and review by a primary care physician who has access to the complete medical record.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Doctors should avoid treating colleagues, friends and family due to potential loss of objectivity and compromised care.","Informal medical care can disrupt continuity of care with regular healthcare providers.","Regular review of chronic conditions like hypertension by a primary care physician is essential for optimal management."],"references":["Bird S. The pitfalls of prescribing for family and friends. Aust Prescr 2016; 39:11\u20133"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75458"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1330"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75458"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T17:27:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T17:27:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1330"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91995"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":nul